  "text": "The Apache Kafka GroupCoordinator implementation is located in the group-coordinator module. The core interface is defined in GroupCoordinator.java, which specifies the contract for group coordination operations including JoinGroupRequest and SyncGroupRequest handling for both classic and modern (consumer, streams, share) group protocols, and heartbeat management.\n\n## Group State Machine\nThe classic group protocol uses a finite state machine defined in ClassicGroupState.java with five states:\n- Empty: Group has no members, awaiting new members\n- PreparingRebalance: Members are joining, group is preparing for rebalance\n- CompletingRebalance: Leader has provided assignment, awaiting sync from all members\n- Stable: All members are synchronized with assignments\n- Dead: Group is being deleted\n\nState transitions are validated in ClassicGroupState.java (lines 111-117) which define valid previous states for each state.\n\n## Request Handlers\nThe request flow is orchestrated through:\n1. KafkaApis.scala (core/src/main/scala/kafka/server/KafkaApis.scala) - Handles incoming requests from clients\n   - handleJoinGroupRequest (line 1368): Routes JoinGroup requests to the group coordinator\n   - handleSyncGroupRequest (line 1392): Routes SyncGroup requests to the group coordinator\n   - handleConsumerGroupHeartbeat (line 2591): Routes modern consumer group heartbeats\n   - handleStreamsGroupHeartbeat (line 2726): Routes streams group heartbeats\n   - handleShareGroupHeartbeat (line 3002): Routes share group heartbeats\n\n2. GroupCoordinatorService.java - Service layer implementation\n   - handleJoinGroupRequest: Delegates to GroupCoordinatorShard for classic groups\n   - handleSyncGroupRequest: Delegates to GroupCoordinatorShard for classic groups\n   - consumerGroupHeartbeat/shareGroupHeartbeat/streamsGroupHeartbeat: Handle modern protocol heartbeats\n\n3. GroupCoordinatorShard.java - Per-partition coordinator shard\n   - classicGroupJoin: Handles classic group join logic\n   - classicGroupSync: Handles classic group sync logic\n   - consumerGroupHeartbeat/shareGroupHeartbeat/streamsGroupHeartbeat: Delegates to GroupMetadataManager\n\n## Core Implementation: GroupMetadataManager\nGroupMetadataManager.java is the central implementation containing:\n- classicGroupJoin (line 6061): Classic group JoinGroup request handler\n- classicGroupSync (line 7294): Classic group SyncGroup request handler\n- consumerGroupHeartbeat (line 4674): Modern consumer group heartbeat handler\n- streamsGroupHeartbeat: Streams group heartbeat handler\n- shareGroupHeartbeat: Share group heartbeat handler\n- expireClassicGroupMemberHeartbeat (line 6664): Handles heartbeat timeout expiration for classic groups\n- rescheduleClassicGroupMemberHeartbeat (line 7047 and 7061): Reschedules member heartbeat timeouts\n\n## Group Implementations\nFour distinct group protocol implementations are provided:\n\n1. **Classic Group** (ClassicGroup.java, ClassicGroupMember.java): Traditional consumer group protocol with leader-based assignment\n2. **Consumer Group** (ConsumerGroup.java, ConsumerGroupMember.java): Modern consumer protocol with cooperative rebalancing\n3. **Streams Group** (StreamsGroup.java, StreamsGroupMember.java): Kafka Streams specific group protocol for topology management\n4. **Share Group** (ShareGroup.java, ShareGroupMember.java): Share consumption protocol for shared consumer groups\n\n## Heartbeat Expiry Detection\nHeartbeat timeout handling is implemented through:\n- CoordinatorTimer interface and scheduling mechanism for timeout tracking\n- sessionTimeoutMs configuration (GroupCoordinatorConfig.java)\n- expireClassicGroupMemberHeartbeat method that triggers member removal and group state transitions when timeouts expire\n- Automatic rescheduling via rescheduleClassicGroupMemberHeartbeat after successful heartbeats\n\nFor modern group protocols, heartbeat expiry is managed similarly through timer scheduling in GroupMetadataManager with separate timeout configurations for consumer (consumerGroupSessionTimeoutMs), streams (streamsGroupSessionTimeoutMs), and share (shareGroupSessionTimeoutMs) groups.\n\nThe assignment building logic for modern groups is handled by CurrentAssignmentBuilder classes which reconcile member state with target assignments and determine member state transitions to Stable, Unreleased, or Reconciling states."
}

